<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-073-242  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 073 242.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Jan 22 1990 v7 n4 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EDI trailblazers pay price for early implementation. (electronicdata interchange)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eckerson, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies pioneering the use of electronic data interchange (EDI),some of whom adopted the technology as many as 10 years ago, oftenhave difficulty integrating EDI systems with their other businessapplications or merging programs implemented by differentoperating units.andP;  New EDI users can implement more sophisticatedsystems than the early users and take advantage of standards thatensure software compatibility.andP;  Software developed decades ago toserve a firm's internal needs is very difficult to integrate withthe dominant ANSI X12 EDI standard.andP;  Off-the-shelf software ismore flexible, but in-house systems may be too firmly entrenchedto replace.andP;  Newcomers to EDI technology can purchase fullyintegrated software packages from vendors such as SoftwareAssociates Inc.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Data InterchangeNew TechniqueBusiness PlanningComputer Systems IntegrationManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>